      • add

        public void add(Type... objs)
        Adds as many types to the end of your list as you want. This method is more efficient than the normal add(Object) method if you add many types. If you only add one type it's less efficient than the other method.
        Parameters:
        objs - - The objects or numbers you want to add.

      • sort

        public void sort(java.lang.String variableName,
                 java.lang.Class<?> c)
        Sorts this list with the quicksort algorithm. If your list contains objects you should choose this method to sort. If it contains numbers you can use the simple sort() method.
        Parameters:
        variableName - - The name of a numerical variable in your object.
        c - - The class of the object this list has been initialized with. Use .class to get the class.
        Example: list.sort("intVariableInExampleClass", Example.class);

      • sort

        public void sort()
        Sorts this list with the quicksort algorithm. This method only sorts this list if the initialized datatype is numerical.

      • flip

        public void flip()
        Flips the list over. Everything that was at the beginning of the list now stands at the end and the other way around.
